If you have built medium-to-large-scale Angular applications, you’ve likely needed to manage custom overlays, modals, slide-outs, or toast notifications. While the Angular CDK Overlay package provides an incredible foundation, leveraging it directly across various feature modules often leads to duplicated boilerplate, inconsistent lifecycle management, and a frustrating lack of type safety.
How many times have you written a wrapper only to fall back on using any for your overlay configurations, component refs, or return data types?
In this multi-part series, we are going to design and implement a production-ready, highly extensible, and 100% type-safe Overlay Architecture using Angular Signals, RxJS, and the Angular CDK.
In Part 1, we will lay down the core infrastructure: the flexible Configuration, the stateful Overlay Reference (CoreOverlayRef), and the abstract CoreOverlayService that handles dynamic instantiation without compromising on strict typing.
The Architecture Overview
Before we dive into the code, let’s look at the three core pillars of our system:

• CoreOverlayConfig: Defines the sizing, animations, behavior, and custom dependencies.

• CoreOverlayRef: Manages the lifecycle, animation states (via Angular Signals), and typed return values of an active overlay.

• CoreOverlayService: An abstract coordinator that creates the CDK portal, sets up the custom injector, manages active instances, and cleans up after they close.
1. Defining the Configuration
First, we need a baseline configuration that supports customizable animations, accessibility (directionality), custom sizing, and injector overrides.
import { Injector, ViewContainerRef } from '@angular/core';
import { Direction } from '@angular/cdk/bidi';export interface OverlayAnimationConfig {
enterDuration?: number;
exitDuration?: number;
}
export class CoreOverlayConfig {
id?: string;
animations?: OverlayAnimationConfig = { enterDuration: 300, exitDuration: 300 };
panelClass?: string | string[] = '';
hasBackdrop?: boolean = true;
backdropClass?: string | string[] = '';
disableClose?: boolean = false;
width?: string = '';
height?: string = '';
minWidth?: string | number;
maxWidth?: string | number;
minHeight?: string | number;
maxHeight?: string | number;
viewContainerRef?: ViewContainerRef;
direction?: Direction;
injector?: Injector;
}
2. Managing Stateful Lifecycles with CoreOverlayRef
When an overlay opens, it goes through distinct states: opening, open, closing, and closed. We want to expose these states as modern Angular Signals for smooth UI transitions (like CSS animations) while keeping our events streamable via RxJS Observables.
By using generics (R for the return value and TConfig for the configuration), we guarantee that any service consuming this reference knows exactly what data to expect upon closure.
import { computed, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { OverlayRef } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { Observable, Subject } from 'rxjs';
import { CoreOverlayConfig } from './core-overlay-config';export type OverlayState = 'opening' | 'open' | 'closing' | 'closed';
export abstract class CoreOverlayRef<R = unknown, TConfig extends CoreOverlayConfig = CoreOverlayConfig> {
private readonly _state = signal<OverlayState>('closed');
private readonly _afterClosed = new Subject<R | undefined>();
private readonly _afterOpened = new Subject<void>();
protected result?: R;
readonly id: string | undefined;
readonly enterAnimationDuration: number;
readonly exitAnimationDuration: number;
readonly state = this._state.asReadonly();
readonly isOpening = computed(() => this._state() === 'opening');
readonly isOpen = computed(() => this._state() === 'open');
readonly isClosing = computed(() => this._state() === 'closing');
readonly isClosed = computed(() => this._state() === 'closed');
private _animationTimeoutId?: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout>;
constructor(protected overlayRef: OverlayRef, protected _config: TConfig) {
this.id = _config.id;
this.enterAnimationDuration = _config.animations?.enterDuration ?? 300;
this.exitAnimationDuration = _config.animations?.exitDuration ?? 300;
this._initLifecycle();
}
private _initLifecycle(): void {
queueMicrotask(() => {
if (this.isClosed()) {
this._state.set('opening');
this._animationTimeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
this._state.set('open');
this._afterOpened.next();
this._afterOpened.complete();
}, this.enterAnimationDuration);
}
});
}
afterOpened(): Observable<void> {
return this._afterOpened.asObservable();
}
afterClosed(): Observable<R | undefined> {
return this._afterClosed.asObservable();
}
close(result?: R): void {
if (this._state() === 'closing' || this._state() === 'closed') {
return;
}
this.result = result;
this._state.set('closing');
if (this._animationTimeoutId) {
clearTimeout(this._animationTimeoutId);
}
this._startExitAnimation();
}
private _startExitAnimation(): void {
this._animationTimeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
this.finishClose();
}, this.exitAnimationDuration);
}
protected finishClose(): void {
if (this._state() === 'closed') return;
if (this._animationTimeoutId) {
clearTimeout(this._animationTimeoutId);
}
this._state.set('closed');
this._afterClosed.next(this.result);
this._afterClosed.complete();
this.overlayRef.dispose();
}
}
3. Strict Typing for Dynamic Portal Content
To decouple our core logic from specific UI layouts (like a Modal Box wrapper versus a Bottom Sheet drawer wrapper), we define how content is dynamic instantiated.
The CoreOverlayOpenOptions interface completely eliminates any by enforcing generic parameters for the Overlay Reference (TRef), the returned data (R), the component being rendered inside (C), the surrounding layout container (TContainer), and the specialized config (TConfig).
import { ComponentRef, StaticProvider } from '@angular/core';
import { OverlayRef } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { ComponentType } from '@angular/cdk/portal';
import { CoreOverlayConfig } from './core-overlay-config';export interface CoreOverlayOpenOptions<TRef, R, C, TContainer = unknown, TConfig extends CoreOverlayConfig = CoreOverlayConfig,> {
container: ComponentType<TContainer>;
config: TConfig;
createRef: (overlayRef: OverlayRef, config: TConfig) => TRef;
providers: (ref: TRef, config: TConfig) => StaticProvider[];
attachContent: (containerRef: ComponentRef<TContainer>, component: ComponentType<C>, config: TConfig, ref: TRef) => void;
}
4. The Orchestrator: CoreOverlayService
The heart of our system is the CoreOverlayService. It is declared as an abstract class, designed to be inherited by specific overlay implementation types (such as ModalService or DrawerService).
It manages hierarchical services (parents and children), tracks globally active overlays, notifies subscribers when all overlays are closed, and safely handles teardown via ngOnDestroy.
// core-overlay.service.ts
import { inject, Injectable, Injector, OnDestroy, StaticProvider, ComponentRef } from '@angular/core';
import { Overlay, OverlayConfig, OverlayRef } from '@angular/cdk/overlay';
import { ComponentPortal, ComponentType } from '@angular/cdk/portal';
import { Observable, Subject, takeUntil } from 'rxjs';
import { CoreOverlayRef } from './core-overlay-ref';
import { CoreOverlayConfig } from './core-overlay-config';
import { CoreOverlayOpenOptions } from './core-overlay-models';@Injectable()
export abstract class CoreOverlayService<TRef extends CoreOverlayRef<unknown, TConfig>, TConfig extends CoreOverlayConfig = CoreOverlayConfig> implements OnDestroy {
protected readonly _overlay = inject(Overlay);
protected readonly _injector = inject(Injector);
protected readonly _destroy$ = new Subject<void>();
private readonly _parentService = inject(CoreOverlayService, {
optional: true,
skipSelf: true,
}) as CoreOverlayService<TRef, TConfig> | null;
private readonly _localOpenedRefs: TRef[] = [];
private readonly _afterAllClosed = new Subject<void>();
get openedRefs(): TRef[] {
return this._parentService ? this._parentService.openedRefs : this._localOpenedRefs;
}
ngOnDestroy(): void {
this.closeAll();
this._destroy$.next();
this._destroy$.complete();
this._afterAllClosed.complete();
}
public abstract open(...args: unknown[]): TRef;
protected abstract _overlayConfigBuilder(config: TConfig): OverlayConfig;
closeAll(): void {
const active = [...this.openedRefs];
active.forEach((ref) => ref.close());
}
afterAllClosed(): Observable<void> {
return this._parentService ? this._parentService.afterAllClosed() : this._afterAllClosed.asObservable();
}
getRefById(id: string): TRef | undefined {
return this.openedRefs.find((ref) => ref.id === id);
}
protected openOverlay<R, C, TContainer, TOverlayConfig extends TConfig>(
component: ComponentType<C>,
options: CoreOverlayOpenOptions<TRef, R, C, TContainer, TOverlayConfig>,
overlayConfigOverride?: OverlayConfig,
): TRef {
const overlayConfig = overlayConfigOverride ?? this._overlayConfigBuilder(options.config);
const overlayRef = this._overlay.create(overlayConfig);
const ref = options.createRef(overlayRef, options.config);
const providers = options.providers(ref, options.config) ?? [];
const containerRef = this._attach(
overlayRef,
options.container,
providers,
options.config.injector,
);
options.attachContent(containerRef, component, options.config, ref);
this._trackRef(ref);
return ref;
}
private _attach<TContainer>(overlayRef: OverlayRef,component: ComponentType<TContainer>,providers: Array<StaticProvider>,parentInjector?: Injector): ComponentRef<TContainer> {
const injector = Injector.create({
parent: parentInjector ?? this._injector,
providers,
});
const portal = new ComponentPortal(component, null, injector);
return overlayRef.attach(portal);
}
private _trackRef(ref: TRef): void {
this.openedRefs.push(ref);
ref.afterClosed()
.pipe(takeUntil(this._destroy$))
.subscribe(() => {
const index = this.openedRefs.indexOf(ref);
if (index > -1) {
this.openedRefs.splice(index, 1);
if (this.openedRefs.length === 0) {
this._notifyAllClosed();
}
}
});
}
private _notifyAllClosed(): void {
if (this._parentService) {
this._parentService._notifyAllClosed();
} else {
this._afterAllClosed.next();
}
}
}
Why This Approach is a Game Changer

• Zero any Types: Every component, output data structure, and configuration block is perfectly inferred by the compiler. If a modal returns a boolean, TypeScript won't let you assign it to a string property in your subscribing component.

• Signals & RxJS in Harmony: By exposing read-only signals (like isOpen or isClosing), we get high-performance change detection inside our modal markup, while keeping the asynchronous event streams (afterClosed()) fully reactive with RxJS.

• Separation of Concerns: The abstract service does not care whether you are building a Dialog, a Sidebar, or a Tooltip. It handles the low-level DOM insertion, portal wrapping, and dependency injection dynamically.
What’s Next?
We have successfully established our core framework architecture!
In Part 2, we will put this structure to work by building a concrete implementation: a modern, fully animated Dialog Modal System. We will construct the DialogService, design the HTML template container utilizing our custom lifecycle signals, and look at how to cleanly pass and retrieve strictly-typed data from our custom dialogs.
Stay tuned for Part 2, and happy coding!
